John Edward: Language skills are a key skill for global citizens
The learning outcomes of Scottish private schools have traditionally been good, and this success has also continued in 2018 as a result of good test results. The success has been enhanced by individual and communal success in sports, art, music and other community projects.
These schools of over 30,000 students, represented by the Scottish Council of Private Schools SCIS, are located across Scotland, aiming to provide a high level of service to their students and their parents.
Private schools aim to prepare their students for their chosen career, postgraduate and higher education, as well as for world citizenship.
As an actor in the field of education who can design and implement customized study content, we have noticed the position of languages as a popular and desired subject in continuing educational institutions.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a person in a language he understands, the message goes to his head.
If you speak to a person in his own language, the message goes to his heart.
This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely only on the English language if we want to establish relationships with the people of other countries.
From this year’s latest test results, we find that languages are at the top of the lists in terms of access rates among private schools.
68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved the highest grade of A.
The data were collected from 74 schools belonging to SCIS. Based on the data, it was found that among students who received the best grade A, 72 per cent studied Mandarin Chinese, 72 per cent studied German, 69 per cent studied French, and 63 per cent studied Spanish.
This shows that Scotland’s private schools support the study of foreign languages as an essential skill that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are currently optional subjects, but are held in the same rank as natural science subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics), both in the study programme of private schools and elsewhere.
According to a survey conducted by the UK Employment Office in 2014, 17% of situations where employers had difficulty finding a suitable employee for the job were explained by a lack of language skills.
The development of language skills is therefore even more necessary in order to promote the future career development of young people.
The more possible tasks require language skills, the more essential these skills become in the global world.
If a person has studied another language, he or she will have an advantage in the future over this lifelong skill, regardless of which career he or she has chosen.
The ability to communicate directly with a foreigner automatically puts a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a survey commissioned by YouGov in 2013, 75 percent of more than 4,000 UK adults are unable to have a conversation in a foreign language, and French was the only language known by a two-digit figure of 15 percent.
This is why investing in teaching languages is important for today’s children.
In particular, the knowledge of the languages of developing countries gives children a better chance to find a meaningful career.
Within Scotland, schools differ in what languages they teach.
Several schools focus on traditional languages, while some specifically teach languages that are supposedly important to the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin Chinese and Japanese.
Despite the interests of your child, there are always several language options in private schools taught by specialized teachers.
Scottish private schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future brings.
In this time period, it cannot be denied that, in an international business environment, languages will continue to be of great importance to the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Today’s languages should indeed be seen as international communication skills.
Private schools will continue to offer this freedom of choice, diversity and high-level Scottish youth.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is director of SCIS, Scotland's Board of Private Schools
