Harvard students complete an adequate rest instruction course
All undergraduate students at Harvard University take part this year in a course designed to increase student rest. The course is a counterattack on the university’s flourishing macho culture, where students weigh long nights with the power of caffeine.
According to the researcher, students at the best university in the world are often quite unaware of the basics of their own well-being.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of medical science at Harvard University, who works on sleep research at Brigham and Women's Hospital, believes the course is the first of its kind in the United States.
Czeisler got the idea for the course after lecturing on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“After the lecture, a young woman came to me and said, ‘Why am I only hearing about it now, in my last year of study?’
No one had ever told her about the need for a dream, which I thought was surprising — she told him in an interview with Telegraph.
For the first time this year, the course will guide students on how the right sleep habits support academic and athletic performance and improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of medical science at Harvard University and deputy director of health services at the University, says the university ended up organizing the course after they had heard how students suffered severe sleep deficits during the study week.
An hour-long course includes a set of interactive tasks.
In one section, students are presented with a picture of a dorm room where the student can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports equipment and books, thus getting information about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the effect of sleep deprivation on athletic performance and the importance of regular evening activities.
In the second section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to reflect on their daily routines.
“We know that this does not have an immediate impact on student behavior.
We believe, however, that they have the right to know about these issues in exactly the same way that they have the right to know about the health effects of smoking - Professor Czeisler adds.
According to Professor Czeisler, the all-night study marathons are still a proud subject, and modern technology and the ever-increasing pressures of students made the sleep deficit a growing problem.
Getting enough quality sleep should be a secret weapon for students against stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, and even an increase in weight, because sleep deprivation causes a condition similar to hunger in the brain, which is why a person is constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student in chemical and physical psychology, helped Professor Czeisler plan the course after attending one of the courses he taught in his first year at Harvard last year.
He says the course opened his eyes and gave the impetus to all campus students to organize a comprehensive course.
He hopes that all graduate students will be able to complete a similar course of study before moving to a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students set an alarm clock to remind them of the time to sleep in addition to waking up in the morning, and urges them to keep in mind the adverse effects of electronic display devices and LED lighting — blue light — on the circadian rhythm, which can make it difficult to fall asleep.
